According to this theory, the fundamental assumptions of Geometry are Proper Aoeiom, or synthetical judgments apriori; and the possibility of forming such judgments depende on the power of con- structing the objects to which they refer in a pure intuition, i. e. in an intuition containing no adventitious element external to the mind itself. The images of geometrica] figures differ from all others in being, not represented modifications of body, but presented modi- fications of space3 and the universal validity of the synthetical judgments is a consequence of the universal presence of space as the form of every possible per- ception of body.
